      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! When you do a high-intensity interval training (HIIT) workout, your muscles are like a bustling city of hardworking little workers, and these workers are your muscle cells. Now, when they work hard, especially during a HIIT session, they produce a substance called lactic acid. It's like the city's waste, but it's actually a byproduct of the energy production process.\n\nLactic acid forms when your muscle cells, in a desperate attempt to keep up with the demands of the workout, switch to a less efficient energy production pathway. This pathway is like a shortcut through a dark alley, but it produces lactic acid as a byproduct. The lactic acid then accumulates in the muscles, causing that burning sensation you feel.\n\nNow, after the workout, your body is like a diligent city cleaner, working to clear out the lactic acid. The body gets rid of it through a process called lactate shuttle. This is like a garbage truck picking up the waste and taking it to the recycling plant. The lactate is transported to the liver, where it's converted back into glucose, which can then be used as energy. Or, it can also be converted into pyruvate, which can be used in the mitochond",
